<section xml:id="list-algorithms-iterators_algorithms"
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <title>Algorithms for Linked Lists</title>

  <p>
    Although implementing an iterator allows many standard algorithms to work with our linked list, not all algorithms can be used. And other algorithms may need to be implemented differently to work efficiently with a linked list.
  </p>

  <p>
    A good example of an algorithm that cannot be used with a linked list is binary search. Binary search relies on being able to quickly jump to the middle of a collection to check if the target value is there. In an array based implementation, jumping to any index we want is <m>O(1)</m>. But in a linked list, there is no efficient way to jump to the middle. We would need to traverse the list from the beginning to get to the middle.
  </p>

  <p>
    Imagine a linked list of 100 elements. First, we would need to traverse 50 elements to get to the middle. If the target value is not there, we would then need to traverse another 25 elements to get to the middle of the remaining half, and so on. We would end up traversing a total of 50 + 25 + 12 + 6 + 3 + 1 + 1 = 98 elements in the worst case. For a list of <m>n</m> elements, we would need to traverse approximately <m>n/2 + n/4 + n/8 + ... + 1</m> elements in the worst case. This series sums to <m>O(n)</m>, which is no better than a simple linear search.
  </p>

  <p>
    Thus, although we could implement binary search for a linked list, there is no performance benefit to doing so. It is better to just use a linear search algorithm, which is simpler and has the same Big-O performance.
  </p>

  <p>
    Any algorithm that relies on random (indexed) access to elements will be inherently inefficient on a linked list. And, for some algorithms like binary search, there is no way to modify the algorithm to work efficiently with a linked list.
  </p>

  <p>
    However, other algorithms that might be implemented with random access can be adapted to work efficiently with linked lists. For example, consider the sorting algorithm quicksort. Recall that the core function for quicksort looks like this:
  </p>

    <pre>
    QuickSort(list, start, end):
      if start >= end:
        return list  // size 0/1 already sorted
      else:
        pivotLocation = Partition(list)
        QuickSort(0 to pivotLocation - 1)  // Sort the first half
        QuickSort(pivotLocation to end)    // Sort the second half
    </pre>

    <p>
      All of the hard work has to happen in the <pf>Partition</pf> function, which rearranges the elements in the list so that all elements less than a chosen pivot are before it and all elements greater than the pivot are after it. In our array-based implementation of quicksort, this partitioning used indexed access to keep track of our location in the front and back of the array and to swap elements as needed. When it was done, it returned the final index of the pivot element.
    </p>

  <p>
    The natural adaptation of quicksort for a linked list would be to implement the <pf>Partition</pf> function using iterators (or pointers) to keep track of our position in the list like <pf>i</pf> and <pf>j</pf> do in the array-based implementation. In a doubly linked list, we could have an iterator starting at the beginning of the list and another at the end, moving them towards each other as we partition the list. When the two iterators meet, we have completed the partitioning and can swap the pivot element to its final location. After the partitioning is done, we would need to return an iterator pointing to the pivot element so that the recursive calls can be made on the two halves of the list.
  </p>

  <p>In a singly linked list, we would have to get even more creative since we can't have a pointer moving backwards. But it is still possible to implement partitioning in a way that only requires a single pass through the list.
  </p>

  <p>
    To do so, we would reimplement the partitioning logic to produce two sublists
    <ul>
      <li>A sublist of elements less than the pivot</li>
      <li>A sublist of elements greater than or equal to the pivot</li>
    </ul>
    One by one for the <m>n</m> elements, we would remove the first element from the original list (<m>O(1)</m>) and append it to the appropriate sublist (<m>O(1)</m> if we have a tail pointer or maintain a temporary pointer to the tail of the lists while we build them). Thus, the entire partitioning process could take <m>O(n)</m> time, just like in the array-based implementation.</p>

  <p>
    Once we have partitioned the list into two sublists, we can recursively sort each sublist and then concatenate them together with the pivot in between. Concatenating lists together can be done in <m>O(1)</m> time if we have tail pointers. If we don't have tail pointers, we would need to traverse the first sublist to find its end before we can concatenate, which would take <m>O(n)</m> time. Or we could simply move items one at a time from the sublists to a new combined list, which would also take <m>O(n)</m> time.
  </p>
  
  <p>
    Assuming we have a size function, the top level function might be adjusted to look like this:
  </p>

    <pre>
    QuickSort(list):
      if list.size() &lt;= 1:
        return list  // size 0/1 already sorted
      else:
        List firstHalf = List()      // empty list to hold elements &lt; pivot
        List secondHalf = List()     // empty list to hold elements &gt;= pivot
        ListNode pivot =  remove first value from list
        // split list into two sublists based on pivot value. List will be empty after this.
        Partition(list, pivot, firstHalf, secondHalf)   
        QuickSort(firstHalf)         // Sort the first half
        QuickSort(secondHalf)        // Sort the second half
        list = Concatenate(firstHalf, pivot, secondHalf)
        return list
    </pre>

    <p>
      In terms of Big-O, we would expect the following work:

    <ul>
      <li>Partitioning the list: <m>O(n)</m></li>
      <li>Recursively sorting the two sublists: <m>2T(n/2)</m></li>
      <li>Concatenating the lists together: <m>O(1)</m> if done with pointers. <m>O(n)</m> if we have to traverse the first list or build a new combined list element by element.</li>
    </ul>

    Whether we do the concatenation in <m>O(1)</m> or <m>O(n)</m>, the overall recurrence relation remains <m>T(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(n)</m>, which solves to <m>O(n \cdot \log n)</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    But an efficient implementation of quicksort on a linked list is more complex than this high-level description. To efficiently partition we need to move existing nodes from one list to another without creating new nodes (<pf>new</pf> and <pf>delete</pf> have large constant factors). This requires very low level manipulation of the data structure.
  </p>

  <p>
    We also are relying on using the first element as our pivot value. Recall that this can lead to poor performance on already sorted lists. In array-based implementations, rather than using the first element of the range as the pivot, it is common to look at the first, middle, and last elements of the range and choose the median of those three as the pivot (swapping it with the first element before starting the partition). This helps avoid poor performance on already sorted lists. However, in a linked list, there is no efficient way to access the middle element of the list and thus no way to efficiently implement this median-of-three pivot selection strategy. We could walk through the list to find the middle element, but that would add an extra <m>O(n)</m> pass through at the start of the partitioning process, further increasing the constant factor.
  </p>

  <p>
    Thus, while it is possible to implement quicksort for a linked list in <m>O(n \cdot \log n)</m> time, we are probably better off using a different sorting algorithm that is more naturally suited to linked lists.
  </p>

  <exercise label="list-algorithms-iterators_algorithms-ex-1"
    numbered="yes"
    adaptive="yes"
    indentation="hide">
    <statement>
    <p>Design the pseudocode for the Partition function:</p>
    </statement>
    <blocks>
      <block order="2">
          <cline>Partition(list, value, firstHalf, secondHalf):</cline>
      </block>
      <block order="4">
          <cline>  while list is not empty:</cline>
      </block>
      <block order="1">
          <cline>    element = remove first element from list</cline>
      </block>
      <block order="3">
          <cline>    if element &lt; value:</cline>
      </block>
      <block order="5">
          <cline>      append element to firstHalf</cline>
      </block>
      <block order="6">
          <cline>    else:</cline>
      </block>
      <block order="7">
          <cline>      append element to secondHalf</cline>
      </block>
    </blocks>
  </exercise>

</section>